2026-01-05 18:46:51,067 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-bdf1215c-640b-4558-8384-8646d30a5dc4', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to fr, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n<p>Spanning more than four decades of work, the show traces Emin’s journey from her early art school pieces to recent deeply personal creations. It includes iconic installations such as My Bed and Exorcism of the Last Painting I Ever Made, alongside the bronze sculpture Ascension and the quilt The Last of the Gold, which appears publicly for the first time. A highlight lies in the candid exploration of themes like love, trauma, survival and transformation, with pieces that confront illness, surgery and disability.</p><p>Don’t miss the early tiny photographs of destroyed art school paintings that open the exhibition, and the revealing documentary Why I Never Became a Dancer. A lesser-known gem appears in the quilt’s A to Z of abortion, offering advice in a raw, unfiltered way. The bronze Ascension stands out as a powerful, tactile response to Emin’s experience of cancer. The show also includes new works never seen before, offering fresh insight into her evolving practice.</p><p>The exhibition observes how Emin’s confessional style reshaped contemporary art, with her use of the female body and personal narrative remaining central. It brings together installations, paintings, bronzes and textiles in a way that feels intimate and direct, inviting close attention to the materiality and emotional weight of each work. The presence of documentary stills and personal objects adds context without sentimentality, and the arrangement encourages reflection on how art can carry memory, survival and transformation.</p>'}], 'model': 'gpt-4.1', 'temperature': 0.3}}
