2026-01-05 18:51:34,441 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-e907a9f7-e10a-439e-af86-91487005996c', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to zh-CN, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n<p>Bright colours and sweeping gestures fill the gallery as Hockney’s recent works unfold across the walls. The exhibition opens with his iPad paintings created during lockdown, including the Sunrise series, which pulses with light and movement. A Year in Normandy stretches nearly ninety metres, inspired by the Bayeux Tapestry, and traces the changing seasons at his Normandy studio. Moon Room offers a quieter moment, where shifting light and time passing become almost tangible.</p><p>Don’t miss the immersive frieze that wraps around the space, drawing the eye from one scene to the next, and the iPad sketches that feel immediate and alive. A hidden gem lies in the small studies tucked into corners—delicate works on paper that reveal Hockney’s process and playful experimentation. The exhibition also includes monotypes and drawings that add texture and depth, offering insight into how he moves between media.</p><p>The show invites close looking: the frieze’s detail rewards patience, the digital works encourage lingering, and the quieter pieces offer moments of discovery. The contrast between bold, sweeping compositions and intimate sketches keeps the experience dynamic and grounded in observation.</p>'}], 'model': 'gpt-4.1', 'temperature': 0.3}}
