2026-01-05 19:08:56,733 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-9cfd436a-b41b-4b8e-ac45-58756d7976b2', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': "Translate the following tourist description to zh-CN, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n<p>Picasso's long interest in performers and costume drives the layout of rooms that read like a sequence of stage sets. Contemporary artist Wu Tsang and curator Enrique Fuenteblanca reframe paintings, sculptures, textiles and works on paper so that theatrical motifs, masks and movement read as deliberate choices in image-making rather than mere subject matter. Over 45 works from the host collection and European loans are shown together, among them The Three Dancers (1925), Weeping Woman (1937) and Nude Woman in a Red Armchair (1932), alongside sketches and costume designs that clarify how the artist tested gestures and poses. ([londonmuseumtours.com](https://www.londonmuseumtours.com/temporary-exhibitions/theatre-picasso-at-tate-modern?utm_source=openai))</p><p>The central highlight is The Three Dancers, placed as a kind of proscenium that draws the eye and opens questions about composition and choreography across decades of work. Don't miss the early Arlequin drawings and the Parade costume designs that explain Picasso's engagement with commedia dell'arte and collaborative theatre projects. A second don't-miss element is the way film and sound enter the galleries: excerpts such as The Mystery of Picasso and archival clips run in several sections, providing the artist's movement and voice as a counterpoint to painted form. Small studies and printer's proofs tucked into cabinets act as a hidden gem, revealing rehearsal-like revisions and decisions normally absent from major hangings. ([timeout.com](https://www.timeout.com/london/news/a-massive-new-picasso-exhibition-opens-at-londons-tate-modern-this-week-091625?utm_source=openai))</p><p>The programme invites responses from contemporary performers and choreographers who appear in scheduled events and filmed works woven through the galleries; these site-specific responses underline the show's thesis that Picasso staged himself as much as he painted. The staging choices—darkened wings, abrupt lighting changes and set-like wall treatments—encourage looking at surface, torn paper and stitched fabric as active parts of the composition. Several loans travel from European institutions and sit next to Tate-held works so comparisons between technique and theme become immediate and concrete. ([spainculturescience.co.uk](https://spainculturescience.co.uk/event/theatre-picasso-tate-modern/?utm_source=openai))</p><p>Practical arrangements follow the museum's usual timed-entry model: the exhibition sits in the dedicated temporary galleries on the fourth floor of the Blavatnik building and runs to the advertised closing date. Ticketing includes concessions and under-twelve rules as set by the host; members have separate entry terms. Gallery opening hours and any scheduled performance times govern access to live elements, so checking the venue timetable ahead of a planned visit helps with planning. ([eastmidlandsrailway.co.uk](https://www.eastmidlandsrailway.co.uk/offers/2for1-attractions/tate-modern-theatre-picasso?utm_source=openai))</p>"}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
