2026-01-05 19:26:36,654 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-786cd7cb-d976-47d7-9a54-de0fe7ad8572', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': "Translate the following tourist description to fr, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n<p>Elsa Schiaparelli's practice casts a long shadow across twentieth century fashion and art. The show traces her experiments from the 1920s through to contemporary reinterpretations, bringing together dresses, jewellery, sketches and loans from artists who worked with her. Highlights include the Tears evening dress of 1938, the Skeleton dress, and the ankle length silk jersey coat made with Jean Cocteau and Lesage in 1937. Loans from Pablo Picasso and Man Ray sit alongside pieces by Daniel Roseberry, whose Matador gown from the 2021 collection appears as a modern counterpoint.</p>\n\n<p>The curatorial sequence examines method as much as glamour. One highlight is the room that sets Schiaparelli's collaborations with surrealist artists in direct dialogue with couture techniques and embroidery samples. Two don't miss elements are the archive of original sketches that reveal the designer's quick, witty line work, and the group of theatrical costumes and accessories that show how clothes read under stage lighting. The Tears dress rewards close inspection for its printed fabric by Salvador Dalí and expert seam finishes. The Skeleton dress offers a study in structure and silhouette and prompts close looking at pattern cutting and padding.</p>\n\n<p>A quieter, hidden gem appears in the study cases: letters and annotated photographs that map professional relationships and creative exchanges, giving a clearer sense of how ideas moved between ateliers and art studios. The displays include three specific kinds of object that ground the narrative: couture garments, artist collaborations in painting and photography, and documentary ephemera such as press clippings and labels. Lighting and case layout emphasise craft details such as embroidery, printed textiles and bespoke jewellery, and the presentation allows inspection of maker marks and construction notes without theatrical fuss. The show sets Schiaparelli's visual wit against the technical demands of haute couture and invites repeated viewing of particular works rather than a single panoramic sweep</p>"}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
