2026-01-05 19:52:30,921 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-435f0a7e-3ba5-461a-9426-81d637f0347b', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to fr, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n<p>Arriving in the Sainsbury Exhibitions Gallery, the Bayeux Tapestry presents a continuous embroidered narrative in wool thread on linen. The work unfolds across 58 scenes and uses more than 600 human figures and 200 horses to narrate events around 1066. Close reading of specific sections such as the Halley’s Comet panel, Harold’s oath scene and the Battle of Hastings sequence brings out the tapestry’s unusual combination of storytelling, technical skill and social detail.</p><p>The display places the cloth against explanatory material and complementary objects drawn from museum holdings and loans to give context to armour, ships and everyday artefacts of the time. A highlight is the Battle of Hastings sequence where embroidered troop formations, arrows and mounted combat compress a complex clash into a readable strip. Don’t miss the panel showing Halley’s Comet for its graphic immediacy and the scene often called Harold’s oath which raises questions about oath taking and political legitimacy. The tapestry’s margins are a hidden gem: they contain small animals, hunting scenes and whimsical ships that reward slow looking and close-up photography.</p><p>Detail matters here. Stitching techniques, the palette of vegetable dyes and the arrangement of captions show a workshop confident in both design and didactic intent. The cloth is useful for historians and conservators because it preserves representations of helmets, mail shirts and seafaring craft that can be compared with archaeological finds. The museum presents plans and conservation notes to explain how the textile is prepared, moved and installed, and those technical displays give a sense of the scale of the operation required to move a 70-metre embroidered cloth safely.</p><p>Interpretative labels link episodes in the tapestry to wider social and material histories of eleventh century England and Normandy, and curators point to local craft practice and the textile economy as essential background. Alongside the main panels, diagrams of ship construction, comparative images of Anglo Norse metalwork and photographs of contemporary embroidery techniques add layers of evidence and invite further study</p>'}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
