2026-01-05 20:32:23,278 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-1b248a31-f67e-4732-a211-986ad59604ee', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to ru, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n{"text":"<p>Curators trace how Pablo Picasso moved between painting, collage and three dimensional work to rethink form and material. The display groups sections on early wooden sculptures and cardboard constructions, cast bronzes and late studio assemblages. Key works include Head of a Woman Fernande in painted plaster, Guitar from the 1910s and the Bronze Woman from the 1950s. The arrangement shows Picasso as a maker who kept reworking the same ideas in ever new materials.</p><p>One highlight is a rare cardboard construction that survives from the cubist experiments of the 1910s. That object sits near a painted canvas study so the relationship between two dimensional plan and three dimensional object becomes clear. Two don\'t miss items are an early papier mache mask with sharp modelling that reads like a caricature, and a later bronze that uses welded metal scraps to produce a face composed of found bits. Those two pieces underline a seam between humour and seriousness that runs through the entire display.</p><p>The show also opens a secondary line of enquiry into tools and studio practice. Sketchbooks, plaster casts and a set of workshop photographs appear next to the sculptures so it is possible to see how cardboard templates were scaled up into bronze. Dont miss a wall of preparatory drawings by Picasso and a series of polaroids of sculptures in the studio. A hidden gem is a small painted wooden head rescued from archives with a faint inscription that ties it to an early workshop assistant.</p><p>Loans from European collections allow direct comparison between works such as Guitar, Head of a Woman Fernande and several mid career bronzes. The curators arranged these objects to show shifting surfaces and the ways light reads across torn cardboard and hammered metal. The display makes technical differences audible by letting textures command attention alongside composition and gesture while showing how borrowing, reuse and improvisation sit at the heart of Picasso practice</p>"}'}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
