2026-01-05 20:34:31,730 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-0f0913d1-9fb6-4c6d-b757-30604258e13f', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to fr, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n{"text":"<p>Displays gather traditional Arctic clothing, contemporary garments and tools to show how people adapt textiles to extreme cold. The selection brings together Inuit parkas with seal skin seams, Sami band woven ribbons, and Thule beadwork alongside recent commissions by northern makers who rework ancestral methods. Specific items include a nineteenth century sealskin parka, a Sami womans ceremonial cape, and a contemporary parka made from recycled nylon for expedition use.</p><p>One highlight is a rare nineteenth century parka whose fur trimming and stitch patterns point to trade routes and changing material availability. Two don\'t miss elements are a display of sewing tools and hides that traces the whole making chain, and a minutely worked bead panel with geometric designs that survives from a small island community. The curators place these items next to documentary photography to show how making fits into daily life.</p><p>The section on contemporary responses brings in artworks by three living makers who reimagine pattern and insulation: an Inuit maker who combines traditional seams with industrial zips, a Sami artist who translates woven symbols into printed textiles, and a designer who experiments with composite panels for polar research. A hidden gem is a small notebook held in the archive where a collector sketched stitch diagrams and noted names and dates. That notebook reveals the continuity of knowledge transfer across generations.</p><p>Labels give technical detail on hide tanning, seam sealing and the cultural meanings of colour and trim. The display also includes a short film of stitching technique and an audio track of makers speaking about material choice. The result is a close look at how necessity, identity and innovation work inside cold climate clothing</p>"}'}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
