2026-01-05 21:00:09,533 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-cfd0730f-8abe-4ee5-87e6-f0e1fde2fea2', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to zh-CN, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n{"text":"<p>Groups objects that invite touch, manipulation and play to show how design can direct attention and movement. The exhibition surveys tactile toys, interactive interfaces and public installations that depend on participation. Specific items include a 1960s modular toy set, a prototype game controller by a contemporary design studio, and a suite of household objects redesigned to encourage playful use.</p><p>One highlight is a reconstructable mechanical toy that demonstrates gears and cam action. Two don\'t miss elements are a side by side comparison of classic product designs by Dieter Rams and a contemporary reworking that uses 3D printed components, and a station where simple programming changes how an interactive object responds. Those displays show continuity between industrial design and digital practice.</p><p>The curators also include a section on urban play with small pavilion drawings, a seating prototype and a public installation case study. A hidden gem is a set of user notes from a community testing session that records frank feedback about ergonomics. Labels explain material systems, actuation and the logic behind feedback loops so the mechanical and software aspects read together.</p><p>Programming offers hands on sessions that mimic professional prototyping techniques. The gallery sets aside space for short term experiments that rotate periodically so the display feels active. The arrangement keeps larger installations at the centre and smaller demonstrators on movable plinths so it is possible to examine joinery and electronics up close</p>"}'}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
