2026-01-05 21:06:00,058 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/chat/completions', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-978b6281-508e-4224-a8f1-c224818f7f94', 'json_data': {'messages': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Translate the following tourist description to fr, ensuring that its inviting and descriptive tone is maintained. Keep all HTML tags intact and return only the translated text.\n{"text":"<p>Charts the visual and technical evolution of electronic music through instruments stagewear and staging concepts. The display pairs hardware such as a Roland TR 808 drum machine with stage costumes and set models to show how sound and image developed in tandem. Specific items include an original TR 808, a stage costume worn by an electronic artist, and set designs for immersive club environments.</p><p>One highlight is an operational 1980s drum machine that runs through pattern sequences so mechanical rhythm becomes audible. Two don\'t miss elements are a case with original analogue synthesiser modules and a reconstruction of a late twentieth century club booth that explains DJ ergonomics. Those items foreground the machinery behind performance and the ways design directs attention.</p><p>The show brings in interviews with sound engineers and designers and places technical drawings next to recorded mixes so it is possible to trace decisions about loudness, speaker placement and visual choreography. A hidden gem is a handwritten patch sheet used by a pioneering electronic artist which records signal flow and adjustments. Labels explain patching, signal routing and the crafts of live mixing.</p><p>Interactive stations let people experiment with basic synthesis and sequencing. The exhibition also includes a curated series of listening rooms and panel discussions with contemporary producers. Presentation emphasises the do it yourself ethos of early electronic music alongside the increasing scale and complexity of modern productions</p>"}'}], 'model': 'gpt-5-mini'}}
